make_test_input_list <- function(var_name, top_4_inputs, all_data)
{
  xvar <- all_data %>% select(all_of(var_name)) %>% pull()
  if (var_name %in% top_4_inputs[1:2]){
    # use 25 unique values between the min/max values
    xgrid <- seq(min(xvar), max(xvar), length.out = 25)
  } else if (var_name %in% top_4_inputs[3:4]){
    # specify quantiles to use
    xgrid <- quantile(xvar, probs = c(0.05, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 0.95), na.rm = TRUE)
    xgrid <- as.vector(xgrid)
  } else {
    # set to their median values
    xgrid <- median(xvar, na.rm = TRUE)
  }
}
make_test_input_grid <- function(all_input_names, top_4_inputs, all_data)
{
  test_list <- purrr::map(all_input_names, 
                         
                         make_test_input_list,
                          top_4_inputs = top_4_inputs,
                          all_data = all_data)
  
  expand.grid(test_list, 
              KEEP.OUT.ATTRS = FALSE,
              stringsAsFactors = FALSE) %>% 
    purrr::set_names(all_input_names)
}

You MUST state if the predictive trends are consistent between the 2 selected generalized linear models.

Based on the results of model 3, we can find that the probability of event increases as the value of xw_03 increases;
Based on the results of model 2, we can find that the probability of event increases as the value of xw_03 increases; the probability of event increases as the value of xn_03 decreases; the probability of event increases as the value of xn_07 decreases; and the probability of event increases as the value of xn_08 decreases.
In conclusion, based on the analysis of the predictive trends of the top inputs, since xw_03 is in both linear models and the predictive trends of both models are increasing with xw_03s increasing, we can make a conclusion that the predictive trends are consistent between the 2 selected generalized linear models.
